sentence: Konrad "Conny" Plank (3 May 1940 – 5 December 1987) was a German record producer and musician.
Konrad "Conny" Plank (3 May 1940 – 5 December 1987) was a German record producer and musician.
His innovative work as a sound engineer and producer in Germany's krautrock and kosmische music scenes helped to shape postwar European popular music.
As a musician, Plank is credited on albums by Cluster, Guru Guru, Kraan, Liliental and Os Mundi.
He collaborated with Dieter Moebius on five Moebius & Plank studio albums recorded between 1979 and 1986.
He collaborated with Dieter Moebius on five Moebius & Plank studio albums recorded between 1979 and 1986.

Plank and the bands he worked with in West Germany had a strong influence on mainstream rock artists, some of whom were able to popularize aspects of his production technique and his distinctive approach.
Plank (who began his career as soundman for Marlene Dietrich) was an ardent believer in the possibilities of electronic music and electronic soundscapes.

On a recording session in Hamburg in 1970 with Hartmut Kulka from the German Blue Flames & Philip Cantlay of Casey Jones & the Governors/Gaslight Union, together known as Kulka & Cantlay, he set up and recorded conga drums with specially inserted microphones to provide an unusual percussion sound.

The 56 channel desk was a custom design and has a number of unique features, including a specially designed equalization (EQ) section that conformed to Plank's own preferred EQ settings, as well as a section which can be removed and which was fitted into a converted military van adapted for remote recording.
It is currently situated in North London at Studio 7, the private studio of songwriter and producer Laurence Loveless.
